# API Routes Structure

## Route Organization

The application uses role-based API endpoints defined in [routes.ts](mdc:src/lib/routes.ts).

### Route Structure Pattern
```typescript
export const apiRoutes = {
  // Admin routes - full access
  pentests: { /* admin endpoints */ },
  
  // Pentester routes - limited access
  pentester: { 
    dashboard: '/pentester/dashboard',
    pentests: { /* assigned pentests only */ },
    vulnerabilities: { /* CRUD operations */ }
  },
  
  // Client routes - view-only access  
  client: {
    pentests: { /* client's pentests only */ },
    vulnerabilities: { /* read-only access */ }
  }
};
```

### Usage Pattern in Components
Always use conditional endpoint selection based on user role:

```typescript
// In React Query hooks
const { data } = useQuery({
  queryKey: ["pentest", id],
  queryFn: () => {
    if (isClient()) {
      return axiosInstance.get(apiRoutes.client.pentests.details(id));
    } else if (isPentester()) {
      return axiosInstance.get(apiRoutes.pentester.pentestDetails(id));
    } else {
      return axiosInstance.get(apiRoutes.pentests.details(id));
    }
  },
  enabled: !loading && !!id
});
```

### Key Endpoint Categories
- **Dashboard**: Role-specific metrics and activities
- **Pentests**: CRUD operations with role-based permissions
- **Vulnerabilities**: Full CRUD for pentesters, read-only for clients
- **Reports**: Generation and submission endpoints
- **Users**: Profile management and role-specific data

### AxiosInstance Usage
- Import from [AxiosInstance](mdc:src/lib/AxiosInstance.ts)
- All API calls should use the configured axios instance
- Automatic authentication header handling
